# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: trie-structure
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:trie-structure/deterministic-acyclic-finite-state-automaton] In computer science, a **deterministic acyclic finite state automaton** (**DAFSA**), is a data structure that represents a set of strings, and allows for a query operation that tests whether a given string belongs to the set in time proportional to its length.
[src:trie-structure/deterministic-acyclic-finite-state-automaton] Algorithms exist to construct and maintain such automata, while keeping them minimal.
[src:trie-structure/deterministic-acyclic-finite-state-automaton] DAFSA is the rediscovery of a data structure called Directed Acyclic Word Graph (DAWG), although the same name had already been given to a different data structure which is related to suffix automaton.
[src:trie-structure/deterministic-acyclic-finite-state-automaton] The strings represented by the DAFSA are formed by the symbols on paths in the graph from the source vertex to any sink vertex (a vertex with no outgoing edges).
[src:trie-structure/deterministic-acyclic-finite-state-automaton] In fact, a deterministic finite state automaton is acyclic if and only if it recognizes a finite set of strings.
[src:trie-structure/deterministic-acyclic-finite-state-automaton] Blumer et al first defined terminology Directed Acyclic Word Graph (DAWG) in 1983.
[src:trie-structure/deterministic-acyclic-finite-state-automaton] Appel and Jacobsen used the same naming for a different data structure in 1988.
[src:trie-structure/deterministic-acyclic-finite-state-automaton] Independent of earlier work, Daciuk et al rediscovered the latter data structure in 2000 but called it DAFSA.
[src:trie-structure/deterministic-acyclic-finite-state-automaton] By allowing the same vertices to be reached by multiple paths, a DAFSA may use significantly fewer vertices than the strongly related trie data structure.
[src:trie-structure/deterministic-acyclic-finite-state-automaton] Consider, for example, the four English words "tap", "taps", "top", and "tops".
[src:trie-structure/deterministic-acyclic-finite-state-automaton] A trie for those four words would have 12 vertices, one for each of the strings formed as a prefix of one of these words, or for one of the words followed by the end-of-string marker.
[src:trie-structure/deterministic-acyclic-finite-state-automaton] There is a tradeoff between memory and functionality, because a standard DAFSA can tell you if a word exists within it, but it cannot point you to auxiliary information about that word, whereas a trie can.
[src:trie-structure/deterministic-acyclic-finite-state-automaton] The primary difference between DAFSA and trie is the elimination of suffix and infix redundancy in storing strings.
[src:trie-structure/deterministic-acyclic-finite-state-automaton] The trie eliminates prefix redundancy since all common prefixes are shared between strings, such as between *doctors* and *doctorate* the *doctor* prefix is shared.
[src:trie-structure/deterministic-acyclic-finite-state-automaton] In a DAFSA common suffixes are also shared, for words that have the same set of possible suffixes as each other.
[src:trie-structure/deterministic-acyclic-finite-state-automaton] For dictionary sets of common English words, this translates into major memory usage reduction.
[src:trie-structure/deterministic-acyclic-finite-state-automaton] Because the terminal nodes of a DAFSA can be reached by multiple paths, a DAFSA cannot directly store auxiliary information relating to each path, e.g. a word's frequency in the English language.
[src:trie-structure/deterministic-acyclic-finite-state-automaton] However, if for each node we store the number of unique paths through that point in the structure, we can use it to retrieve the index of a word, or a word given its index.
[src:trie-structure/deterministic-acyclic-finite-state-automaton] The auxiliary information can then be stored in an array.
[src:trie-structure/hash-array-mapped-trie] A **hash array mapped trie** (**HAMT**, /ˈhæmt/) is an implementation of an associative array that combines the characteristics of a hash table and an array mapped trie.
[src:trie-structure/hash-array-mapped-trie] It is a refined version of the more general notion of a hash tree.
[src:trie-structure/hash-array-mapped-trie] A HAMT is an array mapped trie where the keys are first hashed to ensure an even distribution of keys and a constant key length.
[src:trie-structure/hash-array-mapped-trie] In a typical implementation of HAMT's array mapped trie, each node contains a table with some fixed number N of slots with each slot containing either a nil pointer or a pointer to another node.
[src:trie-structure/hash-array-mapped-trie] As allocating space for N pointers for each node would be expensive, each node instead contains a bitmap which is N bits long where each bit indicates the presence of a non-nil pointer.
[src:trie-structure/hash-array-mapped-trie] This is followed by an array of pointers equal in length to the number of ones in the bitmap (its Hamming weight).
[src:trie-structure/hash-array-mapped-trie] The hash array mapped trie achieves almost hash table-like speed while using memory much more economically.
[src:trie-structure/hash-array-mapped-trie] Also, a hash table may have to be periodically resized, an expensive operation, whereas HAMTs grow dynamically.
[src:trie-structure/hash-array-mapped-trie] Generally, HAMT performance is improved by a larger root table with some multiple of N slots; some HAMT variants allow the root to grow lazily with negligible impact on performance.
[src:trie-structure/hash-array-mapped-trie] Implementation of a HAMT involves the use of the population count function, which counts the number of ones in the binary representation of a number.
[src:trie-structure/hash-array-mapped-trie] This operation is available in many instruction set architectures, but it is available in only some high-level languages.
[src:trie-structure/hash-array-mapped-trie] Although population count can be implemented in software in O(1) time using a series of shift and add instructions, doing so may perform the operation an order of magnitude slower.
[src:trie-structure/hash-array-mapped-trie] The programming languages Clojure, Scala, and Frege use a persistent variant of hash array mapped tries for their native hash map type.
[src:trie-structure/hash-array-mapped-trie] The Haskell library "unordered-containers" uses the same to implement persistent map and set data structures.
[src:trie-structure/hash-array-mapped-trie] Another Haskell library "stm-containers" adapts the algorithm for use in the context of software transactional memory.
[src:trie-structure/hash-array-mapped-trie] A JavaScript HAMT library based on the Clojure implementation is also available.
[src:trie-structure/hash-array-mapped-trie] The Rubinius implementation of Ruby includes a HAMT, mostly written in Ruby but with 3 primitives.
[src:trie-structure/hash-array-mapped-trie] Large maps in Erlang use a persistent HAMT representation internally since release 18.0.
[src:trie-structure/hash-array-mapped-trie] The Pony programming language uses a HAMT for the hash map in its persistent collections package.
[src:trie-structure/hash-array-mapped-trie] The im and im-rc crates, which provide persistent collection types for the Rust programming language, use a HAMT for their persistent hash tables and hash sets.
[src:trie-structure/hash-array-mapped-trie] The concurrent lock-free version of the hash trie called Ctrie is a mutable thread-safe implementation which ensures progress.
[src:trie-structure/hash-array-mapped-trie] The data-structure has been proven to be correct - Ctrie operations have been shown to have the atomicity, linearizability and lock-freedom properties.
[src:trie-structure/hash-array-mapped-trie] In 2017, Michael Steindorfer introduced CHAMP (Compressed Hash-Array Mapped Prefix-tree), an evolution of the HAMT that uses less space and improves performance for some operations, primarily iteration and equality testing (comparison of two collections).
[src:trie-structure/hash-array-mapped-trie] The primary difference is that where a HAMT node uses a single bitmap and storage vector for both elements and child nodes, CHAMP uses separate bitmaps for the elements and child nodes (they must have no 1 bits in common), and stores elements and child nodes in different regions of the vector.
[src:trie-structure/hat-trie] The **HAT-trie** is a type of radix trie that uses array nodes to collect individual key–value pairs under radix nodes and hash buckets into an associative array.
[src:trie-structure/hat-trie] Unlike a simple hash table, HAT-tries store key–value in an ordered collection.
[src:trie-structure/hat-trie] The original inventors are Nikolas Askitis and Ranjan Sinha.
[src:trie-structure/hat-trie] Askitis & Zobel showed that building and accessing the HAT-trie key/value collection is considerably faster than other sorted access methods and is comparable to the array hash which is an unsorted collection.
[src:trie-structure/hat-trie] This is due to the cache-friendly nature of the data structure which attempts to group access to data in time and space into the 64 byte cache line size of the modern CPU.
[src:trie-structure/hat-trie] A new HAT-trie starts out as a NULL pointer representing an empty node.
[src:trie-structure/hat-trie] The first added key allocates the smallest array node and copies into it the key/value pair, which becomes the first root of the trie.
[src:trie-structure/hat-trie] Each subsequent key/value pair is added to the initial array node until a maximum size is reached, after which the node is burst by re-distributing its keys into a hash bucket with new underlying array nodes, one for each occupied hash slot in the bucket.
[src:trie-structure/hat-trie] The hash bucket becomes the new root of the trie.
[src:trie-structure/hat-trie] The key strings are stored in the array nodes with a length encoding byte prefixed to the key value bytes.
[src:trie-structure/hat-trie] The value associated with each key can be stored either in-line alternating with the key strings, or placed in a second array, e.g., memory immediately after and joined to the array node.
[src:trie-structure/hat-trie] Once the trie has grown into its first hash bucket node, the hash bucket distributes new keys according to a hash function of the key value into array nodes contained underneath the bucket node.
[src:trie-structure/hat-trie] Keys continue to be added until a maximum number of keys for a particular hash bucket node is reached.
[src:trie-structure/hat-trie] The bucket contents are then re-distributed into a new radix node according to the stored key value's first character, which replaces the hash bucket node as the trie root (e.g. see Burstsort).
[src:trie-structure/hat-trie] The existing keys and values contained in the hash bucket are each shortened by one character and placed under the new radix node in a set of new array nodes.
[src:trie-structure/hat-trie] Sorted access to the collection is provided by enumerating keys into a cursor by branching down the radix trie to assemble the leading characters, ending at either a hash bucket or an array node.
[src:trie-structure/hat-trie] Pointers to the keys contained in the hash bucket or array node are assembled into an array that is part of the cursor for sorting.
[src:trie-structure/hat-trie] Since there is a maximum number of keys in a hash bucket or array node, there is a pre-set fixed limit to the size of the cursor at all points in time.
[src:trie-structure/hat-trie] After the keys for the hash bucket or array node are exhausted by get-next (or get-previous) (see Iterator) the cursor is moved into the next radix node entry and the process repeats.
[src:trie-structure/radix-tree] In computer science, a **radix tree** (also **radix trie** or **compact prefix tree** or **compressed trie**) is a data structure that represents a space-optimized trie (prefix tree) in which each node that is the only child is merged with its parent.
[src:trie-structure/radix-tree] The number of children of every internal node is at most the radix r of the radix tree, where r = 2x for some integer x ≥ 1.
[src:trie-structure/radix-tree] Unlike regular trees, edges can be labeled with sequences of elements as well as single elements.
[src:trie-structure/radix-tree] This makes radix trees much more efficient for small sets (especially if the strings are long) and for sets of strings that share long prefixes.
[src:trie-structure/radix-tree] Unlike regular trees (where whole keys are compared *en masse* from their beginning up to the point of inequality), the key at each node is compared chunk-of-bits by chunk-of-bits, where the quantity of bits in that chunk at that node is the radix r of the radix trie.
[src:trie-structure/radix-tree] When r is 2, the radix trie is binary (i.e., compare that node's 1-bit portion of the key), which minimizes sparseness at the expense of maximizing trie depth—i.e., maximizing up to conflation of nondiverging bit-strings in the key.
[src:trie-structure/radix-tree] When r ≥ 4 is a power of 2, then the radix trie is an r-ary trie, which lessens the depth of the radix trie at the expense of potential sparseness.
[src:trie-structure/radix-tree] As an optimization, edge labels can be stored in constant size by using two pointers to a string (for the first and last elements).
[src:trie-structure/radix-tree] Note that although the examples in this article show strings as sequences of characters, the type of the string elements can be chosen arbitrarily; for example, as a bit or byte of the string representation when using multibyte character encodings or Unicode.
[src:trie-structure/radix-tree] Radix trees are useful for constructing associative arrays with keys that can be expressed as strings.
[src:trie-structure/radix-tree] They find particular application in the area of IP routing, where the ability to contain large ranges of values with a few exceptions is particularly suited to the hierarchical organization of IP addresses.
[src:trie-structure/radix-tree] They are also used for inverted indexes of text documents in information retrieval.
[src:trie-structure/radix-tree] Radix trees support insertion, deletion, and searching operations.
[src:trie-structure/radix-tree] Insertion adds a new string to the trie while trying to minimize the amount of data stored.
[src:trie-structure/radix-tree] Deletion removes a string from the trie.
[src:trie-structure/radix-tree] Searching operations include (but are not necessarily limited to) exact lookup, find predecessor, find successor, and find all strings with a prefix.
[src:trie-structure/radix-tree] All of these operations are O(*k*) where k is the maximum length of all strings in the set, where length is measured in the quantity of bits equal to the radix of the radix trie.
[src:trie-structure/radix-tree] The lookup operation determines if a string exists in a trie.
[src:trie-structure/radix-tree] Most operations modify this approach in some way to handle their specific tasks.
[src:trie-structure/radix-tree] For instance, the node where a string terminates may be of importance.
[src:trie-structure/radix-tree] This operation is similar to tries except that some edges consume multiple elements.
[src:trie-structure/radix-tree] The following pseudo code assumes that these methods and members exist.
[src:trie-structure/radix-tree] To insert a string, we search the tree until we can make no further progress.
[src:trie-structure/radix-tree] At this point we either add a new outgoing edge labeled with all remaining elements in the input string, or if there is already an outgoing edge sharing a prefix with the remaining input string, we split it into two edges (the first labeled with the common prefix) and proceed.
[src:trie-structure/radix-tree] This splitting step ensures that no node has more children than there are possible string elements.
[src:trie-structure/radix-tree] Several cases of insertion are shown below.
[src:trie-structure/radix-tree] It is assumed that edges can be labelled with empty strings to terminate strings where necessary and that the root has no incoming edge.
[src:trie-structure/radix-tree] To delete a string x from a tree, we first locate the leaf representing x.
[src:trie-structure/radix-tree] Then, assuming x exists, we remove the corresponding leaf node.
[src:trie-structure/radix-tree] If the parent of our leaf node has only one other child, then that child's incoming label is appended to the parent's incoming label and the child is removed.
[src:trie-structure/radix-tree] The data structure was invented in 1968 by Donald R.
[src:trie-structure/radix-tree] Morrison, with whom it is primarily associated, and by Gernot Gwehenberger.
[src:trie-structure/radix-tree] Donald Knuth, pages 498–500 in Volume III of The Art of Computer Programming, calls these "Patricia's trees", presumably after the acronym in the title of Morrison's paper: "PATRICIA - Practical Algorithm to Retrieve Information Coded in Alphanumeric".
[src:trie-structure/radix-tree] Today, Patricia trees are seen as radix trees with radix equals 2, which means that each bit of the key is compared individually and each node is a two-way (i.e., left versus right) branch.
[src:trie-structure/radix-tree] Unlike balanced trees, radix trees permit lookup, insertion, and deletion in O(*k*) time rather than O(log *n*).
[src:trie-structure/radix-tree] This does not seem like an advantage, since normally *k* ≥ log *n*, but in a balanced tree every comparison is a string comparison requiring O(*k*) worst-case time, many of which are slow in practice due to long common prefixes (in the case where comparisons begin at the start of the string).
[src:trie-structure/radix-tree] In a trie, all comparisons require constant time, but it takes *m* comparisons to look up a string of length *m*.
[src:trie-structure/radix-tree] Radix trees can perform these operations with fewer comparisons, and require many fewer nodes.
[src:trie-structure/radix-tree] Radix trees also share the disadvantages of tries, however: as they can only be applied to strings of elements or elements with an efficiently reversible mapping to strings, they lack the full generality of balanced search trees, which apply to any data type with a total ordering.
[src:trie-structure/radix-tree] A reversible mapping to strings can be used to produce the required total ordering for balanced search trees, but not the other way around.
[src:trie-structure/radix-tree] This can also be problematic if a data type only provides a comparison operation, but not a (de)serialization operation.
[src:trie-structure/radix-tree] Hash tables are commonly said to have expected O(1) insertion and deletion times, but this is only true when considering computation of the hash of the key to be a constant-time operation.
[src:trie-structure/radix-tree] When hashing the key is taken into account, hash tables have expected O(*k*) insertion and deletion times, but may take longer in the worst case depending on how collisions are handled.
[src:trie-structure/radix-tree] Radix trees have worst-case O(*k*) insertion and deletion.
[src:trie-structure/radix-tree] The successor/predecessor operations of radix trees are also not implemented by hash tables.
[src:trie-structure/radix-tree] A common extension of radix trees uses two colors of nodes, "black" and "white".
[src:trie-structure/radix-tree] To check if a given string is stored in the tree, the search starts from the top and follows the edges of the input string until no further progress can be made.
[src:trie-structure/radix-tree] If the search string is consumed and the final node is a black node, the search has failed; if it is white, the search has succeeded.
[src:trie-structure/radix-tree] This makes possible to add a large range of strings with a common prefix to the tree, using white nodes, then remove a small set of "exceptions" in a space-efficient manner by *inserting* them using black nodes.
[src:trie-structure/radix-tree] The **HAT-trie** is a cache-conscious data structure based on radix trees that offers efficient string storage and retrieval, and ordered iterations.
[src:trie-structure/radix-tree] Performance, with respect to both time and space, is comparable to the cache-conscious hashtable.
[src:trie-structure/radix-tree] A **PATRICIA** trie is a special variant of the radix 2 (binary) trie, in which rather than explicitly store every bit of every key, the nodes store only the position of the first bit which differentiates two sub-trees.
[src:trie-structure/radix-tree] During traversal the algorithm examines the indexed bit of the search key and chooses the left or right sub-tree as appropriate.
[src:trie-structure/radix-tree] Notable features of the PATRICIA trie include that the trie only requires one node to be inserted for every unique key stored, making PATRICIA much more compact than a standard binary trie.
[src:trie-structure/radix-tree] Also, since the actual keys are no longer explicitly stored it is necessary to perform one full key comparison on the indexed record in order to confirm a match.
[src:trie-structure/radix-tree] In this respect PATRICIA bears a certain resemblance to indexing using a hash table.
[src:trie-structure/radix-tree] The **adaptive radix tree** is a radix tree variant that integrates adaptive node sizes to the radix tree.
[src:trie-structure/radix-tree] One major drawback of the usual radix trees is the use of space, because it uses a constant node size in every level.
[src:trie-structure/radix-tree] The major difference between the radix tree and the adaptive radix tree is its variable size for each node based on the number of child elements, which grows while adding new entries.
[src:trie-structure/radix-tree] Hence, the adaptive radix tree leads to a better use of space without reducing its speed.
[src:trie-structure/radix-tree] A common practice is to relax the criteria of disallowing parents with only one child in situations where the parent represents a valid key in the data set.
[src:trie-structure/radix-tree] This variant of radix tree achieves a higher space efficiency than the one which only allows internal nodes with at least two children.
[src:trie-structure/ternary-search-tree] In computer science, a **ternary search tree** is a type of trie (sometimes called a *prefix tree*) where nodes are arranged in a manner similar to a binary search tree, but with up to three children rather than the binary tree's limit of two.
[src:trie-structure/ternary-search-tree] Like other prefix trees, a ternary search tree can be used as an associative map structure with the ability for incremental string search.
[src:trie-structure/ternary-search-tree] However, ternary search trees are more space efficient compared to standard prefix trees, at the cost of speed.
[src:trie-structure/ternary-search-tree] Common applications for ternary search trees include spell-checking and auto-completion.
[src:trie-structure/ternary-search-tree] A node may also have a pointer to its parent node as well as an indicator as to whether or not the node marks the end of a word.
[src:trie-structure/ternary-search-tree] The *lo kid* pointer must point to a node whose character value is *less than the current node*.
[src:trie-structure/ternary-search-tree] The *hi kid* pointer must point to a node whose character is *greater than the current node*.
[src:trie-structure/ternary-search-tree] The *equal kid* points to the next character in the word.
[src:trie-structure/ternary-search-tree] As with other trie data structures, each node in a ternary search tree represents a prefix of the stored strings.
[src:trie-structure/ternary-search-tree] All strings in the middle subtree of a node start with that prefix.
[src:trie-structure/ternary-search-tree] Inserting a value into a ternary search can be defined recursively or iteratively much as lookups are defined.
[src:trie-structure/ternary-search-tree] This recursive method is continually called on nodes of the tree given a key which gets progressively shorter by pruning characters off the front of the key.
[src:trie-structure/ternary-search-tree] If this method reaches a node that has not been created, it creates the node and assigns it the character value of the first character in the key.
[src:trie-structure/ternary-search-tree] Whether a new node is created or not, the method checks to see if the first character in the string is greater than or less than the character value in the node and makes a recursive call on the appropriate node as in the lookup operation.
[src:trie-structure/ternary-search-tree] If, however, the key's first character is equal to the node's value then the insertion procedure is called on the equal kid and the key's first character is pruned away.
[src:trie-structure/ternary-search-tree] Like binary search trees and other data structures, ternary search trees can become degenerate depending on the order of the keys.
[src:trie-structure/ternary-search-tree] Inserting keys in alphabetical order is one way to attain the worst possible degenerate tree.
[src:trie-structure/ternary-search-tree] Inserting the keys in random order often produces a well-balanced tree.
[src:trie-structure/ternary-search-tree] To look up a particular node or the data associated with a node, a string key is needed.
[src:trie-structure/ternary-search-tree] A lookup procedure begins by checking the root node of the tree and determining which of the following conditions has occurred.
[src:trie-structure/ternary-search-tree] If the first character of the string is less than the character in the root node, a recursive lookup can be called on the tree whose root is the lo kid of the current root.
[src:trie-structure/ternary-search-tree] Similarly, if the first character is greater than the current node in the tree, then a recursive call can be made to the tree whose root is the hi kid of the current node.
[src:trie-structure/ternary-search-tree] As a final case, if the first character of the string is equal to the character of the current node then the function returns the node if there are no more characters in the key.
[src:trie-structure/ternary-search-tree] If there are more characters in the key then the first character of the key must be removed and a recursive call is made given the equal kid node and the modified key.
[src:trie-structure/ternary-search-tree] This can also be written in a non-recursive way by using a pointer to the current node and a pointer to the current character of the key.
[src:trie-structure/ternary-search-tree] The delete operation consists of searching for a key string in the search tree and finding a node, called firstMid in the below pseudocode, such that the path from the middle child of firstMid to the end of the search path for the key string has no left or right children.
[src:trie-structure/ternary-search-tree] This would represent a unique suffix in the ternary tree corresponding to the key string.
[src:trie-structure/ternary-search-tree] If there is no such path, this means that the key string is either fully contained as a prefix of another string, or is not in the search tree.
[src:trie-structure/ternary-search-tree] Many implementations make use of an end of string character to ensure only the latter case occurs.
[src:trie-structure/ternary-search-tree] The path is then deleted from firstMid.mid to the end of the search path.
[src:trie-structure/ternary-search-tree] In the case that firstMid is the root, the key string must have been the last string in the tree, and thus the root is set to null after the deletion.
[src:trie-structure/ternary-search-tree] The running time of ternary search trees varies significantly with the input.
[src:trie-structure/ternary-search-tree] Ternary search trees run best when given several *similar strings*, especially when those strings *share a common prefix*.
[src:trie-structure/ternary-search-tree] Alternatively, ternary search trees are effective when storing a large number of relatively *short strings* (such as words in a dictionary).
[src:trie-structure/ternary-search-tree] Running times for ternary search trees are similar to binary search trees, in that they typically run in logarithmic time, but can run in linear time in the degenerate (worst) case.
[src:trie-structure/ternary-search-tree] Further, the size of the strings must also be kept in mind when considering runtime.
[src:trie-structure/ternary-search-tree] For example, in the search path for a string of length *k*, there will be *k* traversals down middle children in the tree, as well as a logarithmic number of traversals down left and right children in the tree.
[src:trie-structure/ternary-search-tree] Thus, in a ternary search tree on a small number of very large strings the lengths of the strings can dominate the runtime.
[src:trie-structure/ternary-search-tree] While being slower than other prefix trees, ternary search trees can be better suited for larger data sets due to their space-efficiency.
[src:trie-structure/ternary-search-tree] Hashtables can also be used in place of ternary search trees for mapping strings to values.
[src:trie-structure/ternary-search-tree] However, hash maps also frequently use more memory than ternary search trees (but not as much as tries).
[src:trie-structure/ternary-search-tree] Additionally, hash maps are typically slower at reporting a string that is not in the same data structure, because it must compare the entire string rather than just the first few characters.
[src:trie-structure/ternary-search-tree] There is some evidence that shows ternary search trees running faster than hash maps.
[src:trie-structure/ternary-search-tree] Additionally, hash maps do not allow for many of the uses of ternary search trees, such as *near-neighbor lookups*.
[src:trie-structure/ternary-search-tree] If storing dictionary words is all that is required (i.e., storage of information auxiliary to each word is not required), a minimal deterministic acyclic finite state automaton (DAFSA) would use less space than a trie or a ternary search tree.
[src:trie-structure/ternary-search-tree] This is because a DAFSA can compress identical branches from the trie which correspond to the same suffixes (or parts) of different words being stored.
[src:trie-structure/ternary-search-tree] Ternary search trees can be used to solve many problems in which a large number of strings must be stored and retrieved in an arbitrary order.
[src:trie-structure/trie] In computer science, a **trie** (/ˈtraɪ/, /ˈtriː/ ⓘ), also known as a **digital tree** or **prefix tree**, is a specialized search tree data structure used to store and retrieve strings from a dictionary or set.
[src:trie-structure/trie] Unlike a binary search tree, nodes in a trie do not store their associated key.
[src:trie-structure/trie] Instead, each node's *position* within the trie determines its associated key, with the connections between nodes defined by individual characters rather than the entire key.
[src:trie-structure/trie] Tries are particularly effective for tasks such as autocomplete, spell checking, and IP routing, offering advantages over hash tables due to their prefix-based organization and lack of hash collisions.
[src:trie-structure/trie] Every child node shares a common prefix with its parent node, and the root node represents the empty string.
[src:trie-structure/trie] While basic trie implementations can be memory-intensive, various optimization techniques such as compression and bitwise representations have been developed to improve their efficiency.
[src:trie-structure/trie] A notable optimization is the radix tree, which provides more efficient prefix-based storage.
[src:trie-structure/trie] While tries store character strings, they can be adapted to work with any ordered sequence of elements, such as permutations of digits or shapes.
[src:trie-structure/trie] A notable variant is the **bitwise trie**, which uses individual bits from fixed-length binary data (such as integers or memory addresses) as keys.
[src:trie-structure/trie] The idea of a trie for representing a set of strings was first abstractly described by Axel Thue in 1912.
[src:trie-structure/trie] Tries were first described in a computer context by René de la Briandais in 1959.
[src:trie-structure/trie] The idea was independently described in 1960 by Edward Fredkin, who coined the term *trie*, pronouncing it /ˈtriː/ (as "tree"), after the middle syllable of *retrieval*.
[src:trie-structure/trie] However, other authors pronounce it /ˈtraɪ/ (as "try"), in an attempt to distinguish it verbally from "tree".
[src:trie-structure/trie] Tries are a form of string-indexed look-up data structure, which is used to store a dictionary list of words that can be searched on in a manner that allows for efficient generation of completion lists.
[src:trie-structure/trie] A prefix trie is an ordered tree data structure used in the representation of a set of strings over a finite alphabet set, which allows efficient storage of words with common prefixes.
[src:trie-structure/trie] Tries can be efficacious on string-searching algorithms such as predictive text, approximate string matching, and spell checking in comparison to binary search trees.
[src:trie-structure/trie] A trie can be seen as a tree-shaped deterministic finite automaton.
[src:trie-structure/trie] Tries support various operations: insertion, deletion, and lookup of a string key.
[src:trie-structure/trie] Tries are composed of nodes that contain links, which either point to other suffix child nodes or *null*.
[src:trie-structure/trie] As for every tree, each node except the root is pointed to by only one other node, called its *parent*.
[src:trie-structure/trie] Each node contains as many links as the number of characters in the applicable alphabet (although tries tend to have a substantial number of null links).
[src:trie-structure/trie] In some cases, the alphabet used is simply that of the character encoding—resulting in, for example, a size of 128 in the case of ASCII.
[src:trie-structure/trie] Each node contains one possible link to a prefix of strong keys of the set.
[src:trie-structure/trie] A basic structure type of nodes in the trie is as follows: ${\text{Node}}$ may contain an optional ${\text{Value}}$ , which is associated with the key that corresponds to the node.
[src:trie-structure/trie] Searching for a value in a trie is guided by the characters in the search string key, as each node in the trie contains a corresponding link to each possible character in the given string.
[src:trie-structure/trie] Thus, following the string within the trie yields the associated value for the given string key.
[src:trie-structure/trie] A null link during the search indicates the inexistence of the key.
[src:trie-structure/trie] The following pseudocode implements the search procedure for a given string key in a rooted trie x.
[src:trie-structure/trie] In the above pseudocode, x and key correspond to the pointer of the trie's root node and the string key, respectively.
[src:trie-structure/trie] The search operation takes $O(m)$ time, where m is the size of the string parameter key.
[src:trie-structure/trie] In a balanced binary search tree, on the other hand, it takes $O(m\log n)$ time, in the worst case, since key needs to be compared with $O(\log n)$ other keys and each comparison takes $O(m)$ time, in the worst case.
[src:trie-structure/trie] The trie occupies less space, in comparison with a binary search tree, in the case of a large number of short strings, since nodes share common initial string subsequences and store the keys implicitly.
[src:trie-structure/trie] Insertion into a trie is guided by using the character sets as indexes to the children array until the last character of the string key is reached.
[src:trie-structure/trie] Each node in the trie corresponds to one call of the radix sorting routine, as the trie structure reflects the execution pattern of the top-down radix sort.
[src:trie-structure/trie] If null links are encountered before reaching the last character of the string key, new nodes are created.
[src:trie-structure/trie] The input value is assigned to the value of the last node traversed, which is the node that corresponds to the key.
[src:trie-structure/trie] Deletion of a key–value pair from a trie involves finding the node corresponding to the key, setting its value to null, and recursively removing nodes that have no children.
[src:trie-structure/trie] The procedure begins by examining key; an empty string indicates arrival at the node corresponding to the (original) key, in which case its value is set to null.
[src:trie-structure/trie] If the node, then, has null value and no children, it is removed from the trie by returning null; otherwise, the node is kept by returning the node itself.
[src:trie-structure/trie] However, tries are less efficient than a hash table when the data is directly accessed on a secondary storage device such as a hard disk drive that has higher random access time than the main memory.
[src:trie-structure/trie] Tries can be represented in several ways, corresponding to different trade-offs between memory use and speed of the operations.
[src:trie-structure/trie] Using a vector of pointers for representing a trie consumes enormous space; however, memory space can be reduced at the expense of running time if a singly linked list is used for each node vector, as most entries of the vector contains ${\text{nil}}$ .
[src:trie-structure/trie] Techniques such as *alphabet reduction* may reduce the large space requirements by reinterpreting the original string as a longer string over a smaller alphabet.
[src:trie-structure/trie] For example, a string of n bytes can alternatively be regarded as a string of 2*n* four-bit units.
[src:trie-structure/trie] This can reduce memory usage by a factor of eight; but lookups need to visit twice as many nodes in the worst case.
[src:trie-structure/trie] Another technique includes storing a vector of 256 ASCII pointers as a bitmap of 256 bits representing ASCII alphabet, which reduces the size of individual nodes dramatically.
[src:trie-structure/trie] Bitwise tries are used to address the enormous space requirement for the trie nodes in a naive simple pointer vector implementations.
[src:trie-structure/trie] Each character in the string key set is represented via individual bits, which are used to traverse the trie over a string key.
[src:trie-structure/trie] The implementations for these types of trie use vectorized CPU instructions to find the first set bit in a fixed-length key input (e.g.
[src:trie-structure/trie] GCC's `__builtin_clz()` intrinsic function).
[src:trie-structure/trie] Accordingly, the set bit is used to index the first item, or child node, in the 32- or 64-entry based bitwise tree.
[src:trie-structure/trie] Search then proceeds by testing each subsequent bit in the key.
[src:trie-structure/trie] This procedure is also cache-local and highly parallelizable due to register independency, and thus performant on out-of-order execution CPUs.
[src:trie-structure/trie] Radix tree, also known as a **compressed trie**, is a space-optimized variant of a trie in which any node with only one child gets merged with its parent; elimination of branches of the nodes with a single child results in better metrics in both space and time.
[src:trie-structure/trie] This works best when the trie remains static and set of keys stored are very sparse within their representation space.
[src:trie-structure/trie] One more approach for static tries is to "pack" the trie by storing disjoint sets of children in the same memory location, interleaved.
[src:trie-structure/trie] Patricia trees are a particular implementation of the compressed binary trie that uses the binary encoding of the string keys in its representation.
[src:trie-structure/trie] Every node in a Patricia tree contains an index, known as a "skip number", that stores the node's branching index to avoid empty subtrees during traversal.
[src:trie-structure/trie] A naive implementation of a trie consumes immense storage due to larger number of leaf-nodes caused by the sparse distribution of keys; Patricia trees can be efficient for such cases.
[src:trie-structure/trie] A representation of a Patricia tree is shown to the right.
[src:trie-structure/trie] Each index value adjacent to the nodes represents the "skip number"—the index of the bit with which branching is to be decided.
[src:trie-structure/trie] The skip number 1 at node 0 corresponds to the position 1 in the binary encoded ASCII where the leftmost bit differed in the key set X.
[src:trie-structure/trie] The skip number is crucial for search, insertion, and deletion of nodes in the Patricia tree, and a bit masking operation is performed during every iteration.
[src:trie-structure/trie] Trie data structures are commonly used in predictive text or autocomplete dictionaries, and approximate matching algorithms.
[src:trie-structure/trie] Tries enable faster searches, occupy less space, especially when the set contains large number of short strings, thus used in spell checking, hyphenation applications and longest prefix match algorithms.
[src:trie-structure/trie] However, if storing dictionary words is all that is required (i.e. there is no need to store metadata associated with each word), a minimal deterministic acyclic finite state automaton (DAFSA) or radix tree would use less storage space than a trie.
[src:trie-structure/trie] This is because DAFSAs and radix trees can compress identical branches from the trie that correspond to the same suffixes (or parts) of different words being stored.
[src:trie-structure/trie] String dictionaries are also utilized in natural language processing, such as finding lexicon of a text corpus.
[src:trie-structure/trie] Lexicographic sorting of a set of string keys can be implemented by building a trie for the given keys and traversing the tree in pre-order fashion; this is also a form of radix sort.
[src:trie-structure/trie] Tries are also fundamental data structures for burstsort, which is notable for being the fastest string sorting algorithm as of 2007, accomplished by its efficient use of CPU cache.
[src:trie-structure/trie] A special kind of trie, called a suffix tree, can be used to index all suffixes in a text to carry out fast full-text searches.
[src:trie-structure/trie] A specialized kind of trie called a compressed trie, is used in web search engines for storing the indexes - a collection of all searchable words.
[src:trie-structure/trie] Each terminal node is associated with a list of URLs—called occurrence list—to pages that match the keyword.
[src:trie-structure/trie] The trie is stored in the main memory, whereas the occurrence is kept in an external storage, frequently in large clusters, or the in-memory index points to documents stored in an external location.
[src:trie-structure/trie] Tries are used in Bioinformatics, notably in sequence alignment software applications such as BLAST, which indexes all the different substrings of length *k* (called k-mers) of a text by storing the positions of their occurrences in a compressed trie sequence databases.
[src:trie-structure/trie] Compressed variants of tries, such as databases for managing Forwarding Information Base (FIB), are used in storing IP address prefixes within routers and bridges for prefix-based lookup to resolve mask-based operations in IP routing.
